			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2008</a> paper:</span><br><i>Evaluating the Visual Syntax of UML: An Analysis of the Cognitive Effectiveness of the UML Family of Diagrams</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/DanielLaurenceMoody.html">Daniel Laurence Moody</a>, <a href="../profile/JosvanHillegersberg.html">Jos van Hillegersberg</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-00434-6_3">10.1007/978-3-642-00434-6_3</a></li>
<li>Original shorter version of <a href="../sle2008s/paper02.html"><em>The “Physics” of Notations: Toward a Scientific Basis for Constructing Visual Notations in Software Engineering</em></a> (SLE 2008 SI)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagM">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> It evaluates the cognitive effectiveness/usability of UML diagram notations from a human factors perspective.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL">T4F: Visualisation</span></a><ul><li> Its subject is the visual syntax/notation of UML diagrams and how visual design principles affect comprehension.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> It performs an evaluation-style analysis (grounded in cognitive/notation principles) to assess UML’s visual notation quality.
</li></ul></li></ul>
